thousands of radio broadcasts,

00:03:51.770 --> 00:03:53.130
and the first thing
I'll say at least

00:03:53.130 --> 00:03:55.320
about the way our collections
are managed.

00:03:55.320 --> 00:03:57.690
And, this is probably covering
[inaudible] that's brought

00:03:57.690 --> 00:03:59.040
up already in this conference.

00:03:59.040 --> 00:04:04.220
But, just, not just cataloging,
but even inventorying the variety

00:04:04.220 --> 00:04:07.620
of radio programs, the subjects,

00:04:07.620 --> 00:04:11.020
is a very complicated
task to begin with.

00:04:11.020 --> 00:04:13.540
Many of our radio recordings
have not come

00:04:13.540 --> 00:04:15.710
into the collection as such.

00:04:15.710 --> 00:04:19.020
They came with individual's
collection, for example.

00:04:19.020 --> 00:04:23.830
Perhaps a famous stage actress
or actor for whom all of their,

00:04:23.830 --> 00:04:27.570 position:56%
sort of, great radio broadcasts
were captured on transcription disk.

00:04:27.570 --> 00:04:30.030
But, they're not necessarily
identified that way.

00:04:30.030 --> 00:04:33.860
Just like news broadcasts have
come in through all kinds of means.

00:04:33.860 --> 00:04:37.610
Government recordings, of course,
but we just, we have thousands

00:04:37.610 --> 00:04:42.190
of copies of just home
enthusiasts recording radio

00:04:42.190 --> 00:04:44.390
from the '50s and '60s.

00:04:44.390 --> 00:04:46.580
And, again, not necessarily
identified as such.

00:04:46.580 --> 00:04:47.880
So, there's a big work

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:51.480
in just discovering the holdings
we already have, and especially,

00:04:51.480 --> 00:04:53.310
strangely enough, even
holdings that we feel

00:04:53.310 --> 00:04:56.460 position:56%
like we've already got a pretty good
amount of intellectual control over.

00:04:56.460 --> 00:05:00.040
There are a lot of people packed
into a 15-minute radio broadcast

00:05:00.040 --> 00:05:01.770
on a disk that may
have two or three.

00:05:01.770 --> 00:05:04.810
So, there's a lot,
work to be done there.

00:05:04.810 --> 00:05:09.050
That being said, what
we're finding from a sort

00:05:09.050 --> 00:05:12.520
of digital curation
standpoint is we've been finding

00:05:12.520 --> 00:05:17.770 position:56%
that there's a very practical need
for first, I would say, staff level,

00:05:17.770 --> 00:05:21.190
quick access to the types
of recordings we have.

00:05:21.190 --> 00:05:23.350
Because a curation project, often,

00:05:23.350 --> 00:05:26.860
at a place like the New York Public
Library is focused either, one,

00:05:26.860 --> 00:05:30.610
on an exhibition or two,

00:05:30.610 --> 00:05:34.980
maybe trying to reconstruct some
collections or build something

00:05:34.980 --> 00:05:36.520
out for a special purpose.

00:05:36.520 --> 00:05:39.400
In particular, educational efforts

00:05:39.400 --> 00:05:43.920
which are among the more recently
really prioritized efforts

00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:45.220
at the New York Public Library.

00:05:45.220 --> 00:05:47.310
And, of course, everywhere,
but it speaks well to the theme

00:05:47.310 --> 00:05:49.150
of this conference, I hope, too.

00:05:49.150 --> 00:05:53.510
So, to give you an
example, like many places,

00:05:53.510 --> 00:05:56.410
the New York Public Library's
in the middle of building

00:05:56.410 --> 00:06:01.120
out a meaningful interface for
the public to stream digital audio

00:06:01.120 --> 00:06:03.610
and moving image in particular.

00:06:03.610 --> 00:06:09.260
The earliest iteration of the
streaming portal for materials

00:06:09.260 --> 00:06:11.410
at the New York Public
Library was actually something

00:06:11.410 --> 00:06:15.500
that was innovated through
the Jerome Rogers, excuse me.

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:18.730
Jerome Robbins Dance Division
at the New York Public Library

00:06:18.730 --> 00:06:22.340 position:56%
for the Performing Arts who acquired
a grant from the Duke Foundation

00:06:22.340 --> 00:06:25.340
to develop a portal to
stream moving image of dance.

00:06:25.340 --> 00:06:30.510
That set of, that access point was
fascinating because it was designed

00:06:30.510 --> 00:06:32.990 position:56%
with curatorial tools built into it.

00:06:32.990 --> 00:06:37.880
You could kind of create
multi tracts of images.

00:06:37.880 --> 00:06:42.000
You could pull in materials from
outside, like YouTube, Disney,

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:45.610
YouTube or other sites and
integrate it with those tools.

00:06:45.610 --> 00:06:48.600
It was really well received.

00:06:48.600 --> 00:06:51.170
Student populations loved it.

00:06:51.170 --> 00:06:54.540
General researchers loved it, but
as all things institutionally,

00:06:54.540 --> 00:06:57.750
as the digital program started
to get bigger and bigger,

00:06:57.750 --> 00:07:01.090
that was kind of folded
into a larger platform

00:07:01.090 --> 00:07:04.060
which has now seen a
variety of iterations.

00:07:04.060 --> 00:07:06.540
Some more successful than others.

00:07:06.540 --> 00:07:08.750
However, it really is
moving in a good direction,

00:07:08.750 --> 00:07:10.480 position:56%
and I mention this for a few things.

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:14.750
Because one is the curation
part of it was initially offered

00:07:14.750 --> 00:07:17.640
up as a public tool,
which was really cool.

00:07:17.640 --> 00:07:20.700
But, I think what we were finding
was staff was loving the kind

00:07:20.700 --> 00:07:26.460
of quick and dirty access to lists
of files, that either we could use

00:07:26.460 --> 00:07:30.290
because it had the proper, sort of,
file codes that we can recognize

00:07:30.290 --> 00:07:33.100
by aisle or even just
the internal files

00:07:33.100 --> 00:07:34.850
that hadn't gone to cataloging yet.

00:07:34.850 --> 00:07:36.470
Because if we knew what they were,

00:07:36.470 --> 00:07:39.540
we could do a lot with
them very quickly.

00:07:39.540 --> 00:07:44.180
So, I think we're at a place where,
while we are really looking forward

00:07:44.180 --> 00:07:48.340
to building out public tools for
things like digital curation,

00:07:48.340 --> 00:07:51.090
we're also really looking at
how useful these things are,

00:07:51.090 --> 00:07:54.210
fundamentally, on the sort
of interior side of things

00:07:54.210 --> 00:07:57.810
to let us get a grip of
what we have and make

00:07:57.810 --> 00:08:01.920
that material much more useful
to the staff much more quickly.

00:08:01.920 --> 00:08:06.700
I would add one other thing, just
a very kind of specific thing,

00:08:06.700 --> 00:08:08.860
so the current digital platform

00:08:08.860 --> 00:08:14.310
of the New York Public Library
digitalcollections.nypl.org is

00:08:14.310 --> 00:08:20.320
starting its next phase of
being aligned with our MMS is

00:08:20.320 --> 00:08:24.720
to have MMS markers that when
materials go into an exhibition.

00:08:24.720 --> 00:08:27.220
So, these are things that
are digitized outside

00:08:27.220 --> 00:08:31.540
of a public request, a
researcher or that sort of thing.

00:08:31.540 --> 00:08:35.130
These materials will be tagged at
the front end of their clearance.

00:08:35.130 --> 00:08:37.660
So, all the rights get
cleared, all of this.

00:08:37.660 --> 00:08:40.550
So that it can be put
into this digital portal.

00:08:40.550 --> 00:08:45.810
Now, they'll be marked with or
soon to be marked with markers

00:08:45.810 --> 00:08:48.770
that will tell us this was
in a particular exhibition.

00:08:48.770 --> 00:08:52.430 position:56%
So, you can go in and, now, the
public and the staff can sort things

00:08:52.430 --> 00:08:56.100 position:56%
on the OPAC to sort of show you, oh,
this was, these were digital objects

00:08:56.100 --> 00:09:00.490
that were part of this physical or
digital exhibition four years ago.

00:09:00.490 --> 00:09:03.800
And, it's very useful for both the
public and staff in that regard.

00:09:03.800 --> 00:09:07.870 position:56%
And, provides a really nice shortcut
for developing educational programs.

00:09:07.870 --> 00:09:10.710
Okay. The last thing I'll say,
and I'll get out of your way,

00:09:10.710 --> 00:09:16.270
is another thing that's been useful
for us to think about how we want

00:09:16.270 --> 00:09:20.100
to manage and curate our digital
files, as I've mentioned before,

00:09:20.100 --> 00:09:22.240
in the context of educational
programs.

00:09:22.240 --> 00:09:24.900
One of my colleagues,
Danielle Cordovez, who's here,

00:09:24.900 --> 00:09:29.370
has been working with a grant
called an NYPL Innovation Grant.

00:09:29.370 --> 00:09:31.190
Something that's awarded
to staff internally

00:09:31.190 --> 00:09:33.180 position:56%
to do something new and interesting.

00:09:33.180 --> 00:09:37.420 position:56%
Danielle has been working on that
project to build out some technology

00:09:37.420 --> 00:09:42.210
that will basically, you know, just
basically be a box of recordings

00:09:42.210 --> 00:09:44.830
that you can take into a
classroom and stream locally.

00:09:44.830 --> 00:09:47.780
That's an element of control that
