but, yeah, they look okay.

00:30:07.910 --> 00:30:11.880
I'm going to talk about the
Media Ecology Project which is a,

00:30:11.880 --> 00:30:14.180
we're really, honestly, trying

00:30:14.180 --> 00:30:19.470
to create what I would call
a virtuous cycle in which,

00:30:19.470 --> 00:30:25.220
by virtue of having access to
archival, time-based media,

00:30:25.220 --> 00:30:27.830
we grow scholarship
about that media.

00:30:27.830 --> 00:30:29.840
Both traditional, whatever
that means,

00:30:29.840 --> 00:30:32.290
but also computationally enhanced.

00:30:32.290 --> 00:30:36.790 position:56%
We produce metadata that makes the
archival collections more searchable

00:30:36.790 --> 00:30:41.080
and discoverable, and we
help to save these media

00:30:41.080 --> 00:30:43.850
as instances of public memory.

00:30:43.850 --> 00:30:46.620
So, I'm going to bang
through the slides.

00:30:46.620 --> 00:30:47.920
They're informative.

00:30:47.920 --> 00:30:49.400
It's also a little bit of advocacy.

00:30:49.400 --> 00:30:52.750
Our goals will take a village,
and this is a great village.

00:30:52.750 --> 00:30:54.860
So, I hope we can do some things.

00:30:54.860 --> 00:30:57.910
This is our WordPress site,
which essentially talks

00:30:57.910 --> 00:31:00.150
about the foundations of
the project but also some

00:31:00.150 --> 00:31:01.940
of the grants that we've received.

00:31:01.940 --> 00:31:05.720 position:56%
Very happy to have an overview of
the project in this great collection

00:31:05.720 --> 00:31:08.500
that was coedited by
Charles Acland and Eric Hoyt

00:31:08.500 --> 00:31:11.660
about the digital humanities
and media history.

00:31:11.660 --> 00:31:16.170
I frame the project
in terms of modernity.

00:31:16.170 --> 00:31:19.610 position:56%
All the media that we study, that we
tend to study are part of modernity,

00:31:19.610 --> 00:31:21.560
and my favorite description
of modernity is

00:31:21.560 --> 00:31:24.240
from the great French
poet Baudelaire

00:31:24.240 --> 00:31:27.200
who called modernity a
combination of the ephemeral,

00:31:27.200 --> 00:31:29.420
the contingent, and the fugitive.

00:31:29.420 --> 00:31:34.470
We have so much work to do on
the fugitive, and I say giddy up.

00:31:34.470 --> 00:31:37.270
So, various contexts and premises.

00:31:37.270 --> 00:31:40.000
Most of digital tools made
for the sciences crying need

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:42.180
in the arts and humanities.

00:31:42.180 --> 00:31:45.610
If every institution tries to
do everything, we're doomed.

00:31:45.610 --> 00:31:49.740
So, we need to think creatively,
think forward, act collaboratively.

00:31:49.740 --> 00:31:53.240
These historical materials
are going to disappear.

00:31:53.240 --> 00:31:56.410
Most people don't realize
that, particularly, maybe,

00:31:56.410 --> 00:32:01.190 position:56%
our students who see 1000 cat videos
an hour, and they can't imagine

00:32:01.190 --> 00:32:03.500
that moving image culture,
for example, is anything

00:32:03.500 --> 00:32:05.330
but ubiquitous and eternal.

00:32:05.330 --> 00:32:07.070
And, both things are just wrong.

00:32:07.070 --> 00:32:10.890
So, we need to wake people
up to that, but we also need

00:32:10.890 --> 00:32:15.190
to forage new direction for the
academic and scholarly community

00:32:15.190 --> 00:32:16.920
to give back to the archives.

00:32:16.920 --> 00:32:19.730
It can't just be a one-way trip.

00:32:19.730 --> 00:32:24.620
So, we want to augment preservation
goals via more online access.

00:32:24.620 --> 00:32:29.330
We want to add value back to
the archives and libraries.

00:32:29.330 --> 00:32:33.430
Scholars and academics can make
these materials more searchable,

00:32:33.430 --> 00:32:36.670
can make materials
searchable across archives.

00:32:36.670 --> 00:32:38.900
These are two huge value adds.

00:32:38.900 --> 00:32:42.270 position:56%
Can even become part of the workflow
if the archives are interested.

00:32:42.270 --> 00:32:45.880
So, the best first users can
help to advocate for what

00:32:45.880 --> 00:32:47.720
to digitize next and why.

00:32:47.720 --> 00:32:50.220
These are three value adds
before we're really doing

00:32:50.220 --> 00:32:51.520
significant scholarship.

00:32:51.520 --> 00:32:53.690
I call this due diligence.

00:32:53.690 --> 00:32:54.990
Cool. All right.

00:32:54.990 --> 00:32:57.000
So, that's what I just said.

00:32:57.000 --> 00:33:02.160
So, MEP is a triangle
of tools and platforms.

00:33:02.160 --> 00:33:05.150
Media thread which comes
out of Colombia University

00:33:05.150 --> 00:33:09.050
and produces a capacity to
make time-based annotations.

00:33:09.050 --> 00:33:11.440
That's really the kind
of searchability

00:33:11.440 --> 00:33:13.990
and discoverability we
want to advocate for.

00:33:13.990 --> 00:33:18.270
We can produce those
annotations and push them

00:33:18.270 --> 00:33:20.910
out to this amazing
digital publishing platform

00:33:20.910 --> 00:33:23.790
from the University of Southern
California called Scalar,

00:33:23.790 --> 00:33:27.380
and once it's in Scalar, you can
link to anything on the magic box

00:33:27.380 --> 00:33:29.460
and really contextualize things.

00:33:29.460 --> 00:33:33.750
But, we can also work to build
vocabularies that people can share

00:33:33.750 --> 00:33:35.670
and actually have common
vocabularies

00:33:35.670 --> 00:33:37.820
so that these different
aspects of search

00:33:37.820 --> 00:33:40.400
and discoverability
are, in fact, communal.

00:33:40.400 --> 00:33:44.410
And, different scholars
contribute to one another's work.

00:33:44.410 --> 00:33:47.490
We hang out to the
metadata that's produced.

00:33:47.490 --> 00:33:51.330
The archives host their
own materials.

00:33:51.330 --> 00:33:55.930
They're the best curators
and handlers of that.

00:33:55.930 --> 00:33:58.140
And, by virtue of this
kind of triangle

00:33:58.140 --> 00:34:00.200
and then additional
computational tools,

00:34:00.200 --> 00:34:06.010
we can try to create the
future that we're describing.

00:34:06.010 --> 00:34:10.090
So, we want to realize a
sustainability project regarding

00:34:10.090 --> 00:34:12.940
media history as public memory.

00:34:12.940 --> 00:34:16.840
Every archivist I have ever
talked to understands this.

00:34:16.840 --> 00:34:18.140
They get it.

00:34:18.140 --> 00:34:20.870
They want, they want to be
part of this, and we're,

00:34:20.870 --> 00:34:24.740
that's our battery is the
enthusiasm of the archives.

00:34:24.740 --> 00:34:28.830
Develop network scholarship in
relation to this online content,

00:34:28.830 --> 00:34:31.080
promote and get more people

00:34:31.080 --> 00:34:34.780
to understand this dynamic
ecology of historical media.

00:34:34.780 --> 00:34:39.400
Support the essential work of the
archives, engage primary research,

00:34:39.400 --> 00:34:42.620
and innovate new forms of
scholarship and publication.

00:34:42.620 --> 00:34:45.850
So, DH is a, you know,
complicated term.

00:34:45.850 --> 00:34:47.950
I actually love that
it's kind of messy.

00:34:47.950 --> 00:34:52.560
People can't give you
one definition of DH,

00:34:52.560 --> 00:34:56.520
but what it means is we're
working across disciplines

00:34:56.520 --> 00:34:59.400
from a lot of different directions.

00:34:59.400 --> 00:35:03.000 position:56%
And, the first thing to make DH work
is you have to respect one another.

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:05.700
You have to understand you're
working across disciplines,

00:35:05.700 --> 00:35:07.000
recognize there are going

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:09.470
to be little frictions
that arise as a result.

00:35:09.470 --> 00:35:12.890
Maintain collegiality and just
find the new research questions

00:35:12.890 --> 00:35:14.450
that make things go.

00:35:14.450 --> 00:35:19.020
In terms of the traditions
of DH, a lot of DH is focused

00:35:19.020 --> 00:35:22.450
on word culture, and
I love word culture.

00:35:22.450 --> 00:35:23.910
I was an English major.

00:35:23.910 --> 00:35:26.310
But, if we're dealing
with time-based media,

00:35:26.310 --> 00:35:28.850
we're dealing with other kinds
of objects, and we really need

00:35:28.850 --> 00:35:32.470
to innovate the ways to deal with
those other kinds of objects.

00:35:32.470 --> 00:35:34.750
So, media thread sort
of looks like this.

00:35:34.750 --> 00:35:36.260
It's a classroom platform.

00:35:36.260 --> 00:35:41.360 position:56%
It's divvied up into courses, if you
will, and if you have a collection

00:35:41.360 --> 00:35:45.400
or an emphasis, we can call that
a course and start to populate it.

00:35:45.400 --> 00:35:47.820
And, start to create
time-based annotations.

00:35:47.820 --> 00:35:50.310
A lot of our work is with
moving image culture,

00:35:50.310 --> 00:35:54.630 position:56%
but I am a firm believer in the
significance of intermediality, and,

00:35:54.630 --> 00:35:59.820
in fact, my new favorite term in
which to think about that comes

00:35:59.820 --> 00:36:04.450
from the theorist Bakhtin
who talked about chronotopes

00:36:04.450 --> 00:36:08.940
and the significance of historical
moments where there's a combination

00:36:08.940 --> 00:36:14.110
of newsreels plus radio plus
something else plus the newspapers.

00:36:14.110 --> 00:36:18.040 position:56%
And, it forms a kind of a chronotope
that we need to understand better,

00:36:18.040 --> 00:36:21.150
and we can really facilitate
these kinds of understandings.

00:36:21.150 --> 00:36:26.680
So, for sound culture and for radio
culture, same kind of capacity.

00:36:26.680 --> 00:36:30.900
This, you create time-based
annotations, manual,

00:36:30.900 --> 00:36:34.190
time-based annotations,
but one of our goals is

00:36:34.190 --> 00:36:37.600
to facilitate how the manual
time-based annotations can help

00:36:37.600 --> 00:36:43.150
train the algorithms to produce
machine learning annotations

00:36:43.150 --> 00:36:49.420 position:56%
and see how that can really super
generate search and discoverability.

00:36:49.420 --> 00:36:52.570
This is not quite what
Scalar looks like now.

00:36:52.570 --> 00:36:55.940
This is like Scalar 1.0,
and now they're 2.0.

00:36:55.940 --> 00:36:58.380
But, you see how it
facilitates a different way

00:36:58.380 --> 00:37:01.740
to put together linked data,
and that's really the part,

00:37:01.740 --> 00:37:04.800
the main significance of
time-based annotations is

00:37:04.800 --> 00:37:09.310 position:56%
to facilitate these linked data
search and discoverability practices

00:37:09.310 --> 00:37:13.470
where you're not just doing a fly
over of the titles of a collection.

00:37:13.470 --> 00:37:17.320
You're searching within the
texts themselves and coming

00:37:17.320 --> 00:37:22.150
up with a whole other way to
imagine what the scholarship

00:37:22.150 --> 00:37:26.250 position:56%
and the future availability will be.

00:37:26.250 --> 00:37:30.270
Scalar has beautiful data in
terms of their visualizations,

00:37:30.270 --> 00:37:34.530
so that's certainly a nice thing,
and this is what Onomy looks like.

00:37:34.530 --> 00:37:37.620
So, Onomy, this is my little joke.

00:37:37.620 --> 00:37:40.790
It's like taxonomy without the tax.

00:37:40.790 --> 00:37:43.380
I live and work in New Hampshire.

00:37:43.380 --> 00:37:46.020
You get bonus points if
you take the tax away.

00:37:46.020 --> 00:37:47.730
Right? Government joke.

00:37:47.730 --> 00:37:50.040
Perfect audience.

00:37:50.040 --> 00:37:54.130
But, it really is to create
vocabularies that we can share

00:37:54.130 --> 00:37:57.580
and deploy, you know,
in a fairly common way

00:37:57.580 --> 00:38:01.740
which will actually enhance so much
of the search and discoverability.

00:38:01.740 --> 00:38:03.920
These are our metadata standards.

00:38:03.920 --> 00:38:07.330
We are very strongly open.

00:38:07.330 --> 00:38:12.040
In relation to the presentations
yesterday, we're all about RDF

00:38:12.040 --> 00:38:16.590
and JSON and creating those
triples and, you know, making,

00:38:16.590 --> 00:38:22.270
making those kinds of
search capacities viable.

00:38:22.270 --> 00:38:25.800
Delighted to be working with the
Radio Preservation Task Force.

00:38:25.800 --> 00:38:30.630
We are actively pursuing
relationships

00:38:30.630 --> 00:38:32.380
with different archives,

00:38:32.380 --> 00:38:35.460
one of which I'll tell
you about in a second.

00:38:35.460 --> 00:38:38.980
And, we're working toward a
special issue of the Journal

00:38:38.980 --> 00:38:42.390
of e-Media Studies which is also
published at Dartmouth about some

00:38:42.390 --> 00:38:47.510
of the activities of the
preservation taskforce.

00:38:47.510 --> 00:38:51.400
We have an amazing project with the
National Archives that really came

00:38:51.400 --> 00:38:54.590
to us because of some
brilliant grad students

00:38:54.590 --> 00:38:56.640
who recognized a new opportunity

00:38:56.640 --> 00:39:01.850
to study what I call the
film studio none of us know.

00:39:01.850 --> 00:39:03.840
Everybody knows MGM
and Warner Bros.,

00:39:03.840 --> 00:39:08.360
but the U.S. Information Agency
produced, like, 18,000 films,

00:39:08.360 --> 00:39:12.200 position:56%
and under these curious
circumstances whereby, by and large,

00:39:12.200 --> 00:39:15.800
they were forbidden to be
seen within the United States.

00:39:15.800 --> 00:39:19.010
That's no longer the case, but
it means that there are scholars

00:39:19.010 --> 00:39:22.180
in other parts of the world
who have been thinking about

00:39:22.180 --> 00:39:25.400
and studying these USIA
films for a long time.

00:39:25.400 --> 00:39:28.430
We're a networked scholarly
platform.

00:39:28.430 --> 00:39:32.170
we can imagine engaging scholars
from other parts of the world

00:39:32.170 --> 00:39:36.240
to start to teach the United States
about its own cultural project.

00:39:36.240 --> 00:39:42.050 position:56%
That's pretty exciting, and of
course, it has many audio components

00:39:42.050 --> 00:39:45.880
as well, including the Voice of
America which has materials both

00:39:45.880 --> 00:39:48.870
at the National Archives
and the Library of Congress.

00:39:48.870 --> 00:39:51.550
So, we're incredibly
excited about that.

00:39:51.550 --> 00:39:54.260
Most of our grant money
has been to develop tools

00:39:54.260 --> 00:39:57.970
for moving image culture, so we've
got this semantic annotation tool

00:39:57.970 --> 00:40:01.380
whereby you can create
time-based annotations

00:40:01.380 --> 00:40:05.970
for different geometric parts of
the frame that will really lead

00:40:05.970 --> 00:40:08.120
to more granular, you know,
kinds of search and discovery.

00:40:08.120 --> 00:40:12.880 position:56%
And, very excited to be working with
some incredibly gifted colleagues

00:40:12.880 --> 00:40:16.280
in computer science who are
trying to teach the machines how

00:40:16.280 --> 00:40:18.210
to identify objects in actions.

00:40:18.210 --> 00:40:23.700
But, also, other kinds of
textuality, like audio text,

00:40:23.700 --> 00:40:31.320
written text, etc. And, we
are reaching out to people

00:40:31.320 --> 00:40:34.960
who have some coding
wherewithal and some interest

00:40:34.960 --> 00:40:37.150
to help develop these other kinds

00:40:37.150 --> 00:40:41.410
of machine reading capacities
regarding sound culture.

00:40:41.410 --> 00:40:45.650
So, we know that we can help with
speech and music discrimination.

00:40:45.650 --> 00:40:48.300
This is part of what came up
yesterday with the conversations

00:40:48.300 --> 00:40:52.360
about pop up archive which is
really great at spoken word.

00:40:52.360 --> 00:40:56.450
But, unfortunately, is also
going away sometime soon.

00:40:56.450 --> 00:40:58.620
It was reported yesterday.

00:40:58.620 --> 00:41:01.790
We can work with different
kids of diarization

00:41:01.790 --> 00:41:03.570
of speakers, separate speakers.

00:41:03.570 --> 00:41:05.940
That's really a challenge
to get the machines

00:41:05.940 --> 00:41:07.630
to recognize there are
different people talking,

00:41:07.630 --> 00:41:09.650
and how do you parse them?

00:41:09.650 --> 00:41:13.850
But, also, the tools that
my colleague, Michael Casey,

00:41:13.850 --> 00:41:19.170 position:56%
who's a brilliant computer scientist
at Dartmouth and who's different

00:41:19.170 --> 00:41:23.920
